1783888613936847	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuBA		item.comment	bn-3si2	{"body":"Started in workspace bn-3si2 (.maw/workspaces/bn-3si2). Root cause confirmed: 'seal reviews list' is repo-global (43 reviews here), not workspace-scoped. ProtocolContext::reviews_in_workspace does no filtering, so protocol review takes reviews[0] — currently a MERGED review for an unrelated bone — and evaluates the review gate against it, reporting Ready and bypassing review. Same unscoped selection exists in resume.rs, status.rs, and the duplicated find_review_for_workspace in finish.rs + merge.rs (those only exclude 'merged', not other bones). Fix: single bone-scoped selector (title '<bone-id>: ...' convention + exclude terminal statuses merged/abandoned), used by all call sites. risk:high — this is the security review gate."}	blake3:uv-m25U1Qx4Z0KD8oTTNPe03Gk8ysrcCQndESDWN3DQ
1783889111330140	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuBQ		item.comment	bn-3si2	{"body":"Review created: cr-3235w1 in workspace bn-3si2. Fix committed a4210e6b. Verified live BEFORE/AFTER on this bone itself: old binary reported 'Status: Ready / Review: cr-2qex (merged) / approved by botbox-security' for bn-3si2 (which had NO review); new binary reports 'Needs Review' + create steps. protocol resume likewise stopped hallucinating a pending review. Explicit --review-id on a merged review is now Blocked. Tests: 407 passed, 0 failed, 10 new; no new clippy errors vs trunk baseline."}	blake3:Yt-MKoqAI7FOrrTbiP8y75Sw71CxI0rYr_BNxNMyKqw
1783889216338336	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuBg		item.comment	bn-3si2	{"body":"Reviewer was never spawned: 'rite hooks list' has NO mention hook for botbox-security on the botbox channel (the only botbox-matching hook is an unrelated manifold-channel one). The @botbox-security mention could not fire anything, so cr-3235w1 sat at zero votes. Spawned the reviewer directly: vessel spawn --name botbox-security -- edict run reviewer-loop --agent botbox-security (cwd /home/bob/src/edict, RITE_CHANNEL=botbox)."}	blake3:TkxGuICvliXUQbTUKz5telR1wAd7sp3fAl5s7Oz_SOo
1783889999454195	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuBw		item.create	bn-1u4x	{"description":"Follow-up from cr-3235w1 (botbox-security, MEDIUM) on bn-3si2.\n\nbn-3si2 fixed the BONE axis of the review gate: a review now gates only the bone named in its title. The COMMIT axis is still unbound.\n\nResidual bypass:\n1. Author opens cr-X titled '<bone>: ...'; reviewers LGTM at commit A.\n2. Author pushes commits B, C to the same workspace. seal keeps the review live and approved.\n3. protocol merge: cr-X is live, titled for the bone, Approved -> merge proceeds. B and C were never reviewed.\n\nSame failure class as the bug bn-3si2 fixed ('an approval that does not correspond to the work satisfies the gate'), parameterised by commit instead of by bone.\n\nThe data exists and is unused: 'seal diff <id>' returns base_commit, initial_commit and target_commit, but ProtocolContext's ReviewDetail (adapters.rs ~166-182) does not parse a target commit. Fix: parse it, and have evaluate_review_gate compare the approved commit against the workspace HEAD being merged, treating a mismatch as NeedsReview (stale approval).\n\nFail-closed direction required: if the commit cannot be determined, the gate must block, not open.","kind":"bug","title":"Protocol review gate binds review->bone but never review->commit"}	blake3:qPk7Ru6m-ygyI7lPOdIRvkO-STDT1J0E0Hb9-1Lhop0
1783890090883109	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuCA		item.comment	bn-3si2	{"body":"Review round 2: botbox-security BLOCKED cr-3235w1 with 2 HIGH + 3 MEDIUM/LOW. The blocking finding was real and self-inflicted: title_matches_bone requires a '<bone-id>:' prefix, but finish.rs:460 passed the bare bone title and merge.rs:404 passed 'Work from <id>' — so a review created by following edict's OWN guidance was invisible to the gate (approvable, still reported missing), leaving --force (skip the gate) as the only way forward. Worse than the bug being fixed. Addressed in ef92aee9: (1) HIGH x2 — seal_create_cmd now takes bone_id and applies the prefix itself via review_select::scoped_title, so an unmatchable title is unrepresentable; merge's no-bone arm no longer offers a create step it cannot bind, and the '--force to skip review gate' advice is gone. Round-trip tests added. (2) MEDIUM — TERMINAL_STATUSES deny-list replaced with a LIVE_STATUSES allow-list pinned to seal's real ReviewStatus enum (Open/Approved/Merged/Abandoned, verified in seal source); unknown/empty statuses now fail closed (the empty serde default was being PREFERRED by select_for_bone). (3) MEDIUM — merge's workspace-name->bone fallback now requires the caller to hold that bone's claim (rite grants them exclusively). (4) LOW — diagnostic when a bone has >1 live review. Deferred: review->commit binding (th-2wspys, left open) -> bn-1u4x. 412 tests pass (5 new), clippy 29 = trunk baseline. Re-requested review."}	blake3:nZrJ_EE4P2j2MeA1C8O7ej50_xQF1-gjs9hRwb9-5Tc
1783890615754659	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuCQ		item.comment	bn-3si2	{"body":"Review round 3: botbox-security confirmed both HIGH fixes (verified, not on faith) but blocked on 2 MEDIUMs, both real: (1) I hardened Method 3 of merge::find_bone_for_workspace while Method 1 returns FIRST and mapped a free-text claim memo to gate identity across EVERY agent's claims — no agent filter, no corroboration; inert today only because Claim.memo never deserializes (rite emits 'message'), which is an accident, not a control. (2) find_review_for_bone checked the SUMMARY status but handed the unvalidated DETAIL status (separate seal call/snapshot) to the gate for 4 of 5 call sites. Both fixed in 6020c0a7: holds_bone_claim() shared by Methods 1+3 (agent filter + held-bone-claim corroboration), detail-status check at the choke point, stale context.rs comment corrected so the tempting one-line serde-alias 'fix' cannot silently arm the memo path. 415 tests (3 new, with Claim.memo populated explicitly so the checks hold once the alias lands), clippy 29 = trunk. Threads th-1o297l/th-442luy resolved; re-requested review."}	blake3:kmlD8fn56VkCohoh1HtrnEk9994IZmWSz8awoKWm6kU
1783890879223704	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuCg		item.create	bn-2lz3	{"description":"Follow-up from cr-3235w1 (botbox-security, LOW, thread th-3k6rrt) on bn-3si2.\n\ncheck_bone_gate's Err arm (merge.rs ~325) diagnoses 'Could not fetch bone <id> — Proceeding with merge', so a bn failure makes the bone-STATE check (bone must be 'done') pass by default rather than block.\n\nWhy it is LOW and not HIGH: it does NOT bypass the review gate. That gate runs independently and does not depend on bone_status — so an unreviewable merge still blocks. The bone-state check is the only thing that opens.\n\nBut it is safe only for that reason, and the reason is nowhere written down. Anyone who later makes the review gate depend on bone_status (entirely natural — e.g. 'skip review for bones tagged risk:low') silently converts this fail-open into a review-gate bypass.\n\nFix: either fail closed on the Err arm (a bn failure blocks the merge, matching how every other identity/gate failure in this module behaves), or keep proceeding but document the invariant loudly at the Err arm: 'this fail-open is safe ONLY while the review gate is independent of bone_status; if that ever changes, this must fail closed.'\n\nPreference: fail closed. Every other unresolvable input in this module (no bone, unknown status, uncorroborated identity) blocks; this is the one that proceeds.","kind":"bug","title":"protocol merge: bone-state check passes when 'bn show' fails"}	blake3:l_DTcQ0QQc6y1c_Im6_Ek_WMSQG60iArcSbeoRLtxOU
1783890942225658	edict-dev/0	itc:v3:AWKeZ-TzMmZyRAAAAAAAQb2_XtrbqAAAAAEuCw		item.move	bn-3si2	{"reason":"Completed — review gate now scopes review selection to the bone and fails closed on every identity path. Approved by botbox-security after 3 rounds; merged as 044a7678.","state":"done"}	blake3:qYMwCpCu8711IXhK-P9RN4IEHWDBhrmCZnPmp2iWuBY
1784666449612123	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHA		item.create	bn-2ni2	{"description":"finish.md (\"Undo local merge attempt and return workspace to a clean base:\nmaw ws undo $WS\"), merge-check.md step 6, and the hardcoded guidance string in\nsrc/commands/protocol/merge.rs (add_conflict_recovery_guidance, ~line 595:\n\"maw ws undo {workspace} # reset workspace to its base\") all prescribe\n`maw ws undo` during merge-conflict recovery.\n\nThat is the wrong verb: `maw ws undo <ws>` reverts the workspace's ENTIRE\ndelta back to its base epoch — including the committed work the agent is\ntrying to merge. (A recovery snapshot is pinned first so nothing is truly\nlost, but an agent following the documented step mid-recovery would blow\naway its branch and then need `maw ws recover` to get it back.)\n\nCorrect verbs in current maw (1.0.0-pre.12):\n- Undo a COMPLETED merge: repo-level `maw undo` (plus `maw ops log` to pick\n  a specific op id). Rewinds epoch+branch, restores destroyed sources,\n  preserves dirty trunk.\n- Clear a stuck/orphaned merge attempt (killed/OOM/Ctrl-C mid-merge):\n  `maw ws merge --abort`.\n- A `--check` pre-flight needs no undo at all — it undoes itself.\n- `maw ws undo` remains correct ONLY where the intent is \"discard this\n  workspace's local changes entirely\".\n\nFiles: src/templates/docs/finish.md (Full recovery section),\nsrc/templates/docs/merge-check.md (Conflict recovery list),\nsrc/commands/protocol/merge.rs (guidance string + the test at ~line 799\nasserting \"maw ws undo\" appears in diagnostics).\n\nAlso in merge.rs (~line 460): the diagnostic \"Workspace is stale — run\n`maw ws sync` first\" is mostly obsolete — `maw ws merge` auto-syncs stale\nsources before merging. Soften/replace it (stale is not a blocker; sync is\nonly needed if auto-sync itself reported conflicts).\n\nAcceptance: no template or protocol guidance suggests `maw ws undo` as a\nmerge-recovery step; `maw undo` and `maw ws merge --abort` are documented\nwith the distinction above; tests updated and green (cargo test).\n","kind":"bug","labels":["maw-drift"],"title":"Fix wrong undo verb in merge conflict recovery (ws undo vs maw undo)"}	blake3:LbY3TN0uqvj1jaYNeO19eYSeVxWyRmnEN8ZUYcEOGn8
1784666449777420	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHQ		item.create	bn-ldp5	{"description":"Maw's primary conflict-resolution surface appears nowhere in the edict\ntemplates. Current maw (1.0.0-pre.12):\n\n- Conflicts are STATE, not failure. `maw ws sync` now rebases\n  committed-ahead workspaces BY DEFAULT (formerly --rebase); on conflict it\n  does not abort — it writes labeled conflict markers, commits them, records\n  metadata, and leaves the workspace \"conflicted but synced\" (visible in\n  `maw ws list` / `maw ws status` as lifecycle:conflicted).\n- `maw ws resolve <ws> --list` shows conflicted files;\n  `maw ws resolve <ws> --keep epoch|<ws-name>|both|union` and\n  `--keep PATH=NAME` materialize resolutions.\n- `maw ws merge ... --resolve cf-id=<ws>` / `--resolve-all=<ws>` resolve\n  merge conflicts inline at merge time.\n- `maw ws conflicts <ws>` inspects conflict details.\n\nThe templates instead teach only manual git restore/add/retry, and frame a\nconflicted workspace as a failure to fix-then-retry.\n\nWork:\n- Add a condensed \"conflicts are data, not errors\" paragraph to\n  src/templates/agents-managed.md.jinja (source it from maw's AGENTS.md\n  \"Operating Model\" section in ~/src/maw/AGENTS.md).\n- In finish.md and merge-check.md conflict-recovery flows, lead with\n  `maw ws resolve` / merge `--resolve` flags; keep manual git commands as\n  fallback.\n- Mention that merge auto-syncs stale sources, and the one hard gate:\n  merge refuses a source whose HEAD still contains unresolved conflict\n  markers (bypass with --force only for legitimate marker-like content).\n\nAcceptance: agents-managed.md.jinja, finish.md, merge-check.md updated;\nkeep it token-lean (these render into every project's AGENTS.md).\n","kind":"task","labels":["maw-drift"],"title":"Document maw conflicts-are-data model and ws resolve in templates"}	blake3:UxHY_DZoo8APC9tKzx5erpnSlffIaAISXQSXq96lGtM
1784666449946304	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHg		item.create	bn-3sh1	{"description":"jj jargon and pre-git-rewrite version references survive in the templates\n(maw is now git-native, at 1.0.0-pre.12):\n\n- src/templates/docs/finish.md step 7: \"maw ws merge now produces linear\n  history: workspace commits are rebased onto main and squashed into a\n  single commit (as of v0.22.0)\" — wrong twice: no squash (multi-workspace\n  merges create a merge commit; single-workspace merges adopt commits),\n  and the version reference is ancient.\n- finish.md step 7: \"Scaffolding commits are automatically abandoned; main\n  bookmark is automatically moved and ready for push\" — \"abandon\" and\n  \"bookmark\" are jj vocabulary; maw itself fixed a jj-jargon leak in its\n  own help text for exactly this reason.\n- finish.md step 9 + worker-loop.md step 6: \"maw push (maw v0.24.0+\n  handles bookmark and push automatically)\" — drop the version and the\n  word bookmark; `maw push` pushes the configured branch, `maw push\n  --advance` after direct commits.\n- src/templates/agents-managed.md.jinja: heading \"Directory Structure\n  (maw v2)\" — the root layout is officially the \"consolidated\" layout;\n  v2-bare is the deprecated legacy path. Rename the heading (e.g.\n  \"Directory Structure\" or \"(consolidated layout)\") — note the template\n  has both is_root_layout branches; only the heading label is wrong.\n- src/templates/docs/merge-check.md line ~27: \"seal reviews mark-merged\n  <review-id>\" lacks the `maw exec $WS -- ` prefix every other seal\n  command mandates.\n\nAcceptance: no \"bookmark\"/\"abandoned\" jj vocabulary, no v0.22/v0.24\nreferences, no incorrect squash claim, heading renamed, seal command\nprefixed. Check rendered output paths too (grep the repo's own\n.agents/edict/ and AGENTS.md if regeneration is part of the build).\n","kind":"bug","labels":["maw-drift"],"title":"Remove jj-era fossils and stale maw version claims from templates"}	blake3:Nnt73FC_oPUGDZliOJJ4TJVbB1_LNPDWlcZ5f4MCX4o
1784666450107456	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHw		item.create	bn-2nhx	{"description":"Maw grew verbs the templates should use:\n\n- src/templates/docs/preflight.md runs only `maw doctor`. Add\n  `maw fsck` as the deep integrity check (exit 0 clean / 1 warn / 2\n  corruption; --repair applies only provably-safe fixes). doctor = fast\n  triage, fsck = exhaustive invariant check.\n- src/templates/docs/mission.md (~line 150, dead-worker cleanup): \"Destroy\n  workspace if it exists: maw ws destroy <ws>\" — this will be REFUSED when\n  the workspace has unmerged commits (the normal case for a dead worker).\n  Update to: `maw ws destroy <ws> --dry-run` first to preview (prints\n  lifecycle state + recommended command), then `maw ws destroy <ws>\n  --force` — noting --force pins a full recovery snapshot first, so the\n  work remains recoverable via `maw ws recover`.\n- Where recovery flows mention sync refusals over untracked scratch\n  files, note `maw ws clean <ws>` (snapshot-first untracked-file removal;\n  `--dry-run` to preview) as the guard-friendly cure — e.g. in the\n  finish.md / merge-check.md recovery sections.\n\nAcceptance: preflight includes fsck; mission.md dead-worker path uses\ndry-run + --force with recovery note; ws clean mentioned in at least one\nrecovery flow.\n","kind":"task","labels":["maw-drift"],"title":"Reference newer maw verbs: fsck, ws clean, destroy --dry-run"}	blake3:Y0KrBlKWgBTUdfyN0aMQPuEmXzCvLEHACXuEoMgkREI
